As the congregation grew, the need for a traditional temple became clear. A Convening Committee was formed on 25 April 1986 and registered as **Hindu Ahlaya Sangam**. After years of fundraising, the committee purchased 4.5 acres of elevated bushland at South Maclean — 35 km south of Brisbane, beside the Logan River — in 1990.

The foundation was laid on 10 June 1993. Stapathies and sculptors arrived from South India to begin the painstaking work. Construction of the shrines commenced on 24 June 1994.

The traditional *Kumbabishekam* (consecration) was held on 5 February 1995, witnessed by hundreds of devotees from across Australia and beyond.

The temple is built in conformity with ancient *Sitpa Sastra* and *Agamas*, with a beautiful Gopuram and ornamental icons crafted by the visiting sculptors — a piece of South India transplanted into the Queensland bush.